<article class="article" id="article_8"><div class='article_title'>
Github pull requests are discussions
</div>
<div class='article_content'><p>I&#39;m working with several students from Mendicant&#39;s January 2012 session and encouraging all of them to SEND ME TEH CODEZ as soon as they&#39;ve got something worthwhile to talk about. <a href="https://github.com/jordanbyron/mission_of_mercy/pull/66">The result</a> has been nothing short of amazing and I&#39;m really starting to see the power of Github&#39;s pull request system.</p>
<p>But using Github to discuss code isn&#39;t my idea. Zach Holman&#39;s talk, &quot;<a href="http://speakerdeck.com/u/holman/p/how-github-uses-github-to-build-github?slide=28">How GitHub uses GitHub to build GitHub</a>&quot; proposes that pull requests are for discussing code. Because of that they should be created right away so the discussion and feedback can occur faster, resulting in better code</p>
